Well, Charlie, it all started back in the spring of 1943 when the Texas Forest Service and the Civil Air Patrol put their heads together and decided to try patrolling the forest with an airplane.
And it seemed like a good idea.
So for about 42 hours, Texas Forest Service observers flew with the CAP pilots to try it out.
And the trial was successful.
And it was economical, too, so a full-scale test was set up.
An active unit of CAP was organized on January 4, 1944, and nine planes were made available to the CAP.
Two-way radios were borrowed from the Army Air Force.
They were installed in the airplanes, and the first full-scale aerial patrol of our Texas forests got underway.
And during the next 14 months, this patrol flew 1,000 hours.
That was just the beginning, and from that start has grown the Texas Forest Service's own aerial patrol.
Several radio-equipped airplanes are now owned by the Forest Service, and the pilots are regular employees of the service.
Other airplanes are under contract, and during this year, these planes will fly several times the number of hours of patrol as was flown that first year.
That original test has now become a full-scale standard operation.
